# {{lb|en|grammar}} [[case|Case]] used to express direction towards an [[indirect object]], the [[recipient]] or [[beneficiary]] of an action, and is generally indicated in English by ''to'' (when a recipient) or ''for'' (when a beneficiary) with the [[objective case]]. The [[direct object]] may be either stated or unstated where the indirect object is the beneficiary of the verbal action, but is stated where the indirect object is a recipient. If there is emphasis on the indirect object, the indirect object usually [[precede|precedes]] the direct object and is not usually indicated with ''to'' or ''for''; said structure is also used when neither object is being emphasized.

